<paragraph blockId="83.[151,1437,1340,1439]" pageId="83" pageNumber="84">
A genus of three species, one of which has been found in 
<collectingCountry box="[795,888,1377,1403]" name="Ecuador" pageId="83" pageNumber="84">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[903,987,1377,1403]" captionStart="FIGURE 44" captionStartId="84.[151,250,812,837]" captionTargetBox="[340,1247,181,793]" captionTargetId="figure@84.[340,1247,181,793]" captionTargetPageId="84" captionText="FIGURE 44. Oxystigma petiolatum, ♂: Guyana, East Berbice-Corentyne Region, narrow sandy blackwater stream with swampy area and roadside pool, about 5 km from camp by logging camp, 29 ix 2014; photo N. von Ellenrieder." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3335753/files/figure.png" pageId="83" pageNumber="84">Fig. 44</figureCitation>
). See 
<bibRefCitation author="Garrison, R. W." box="[1054,1234,1377,1403]" pageId="83" pageNumber="84" pagination="347 - 364" refId="ref190451" refString="Garrison, R. W. (2014) Review of Oxystigma Selys with the synonymy of Oxystigma williamsoni Geijskes (Odonata Heteragrionidae). Zootaxa, 3780 (2), 347 - 364. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3780.2.7" type="journal article" year="2014">Garrison (2014)</bibRefCitation>
for identification. Adults are active in light rainfall. Habitat is small streams at various elevations.
</paragraph>
